'''Kameyama Hachimangu''' (かめやまはちまんぐう) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|en|Nagasaki Prefecture|qid=Q169376|lt=Nagasaki Prefecture|1=Nagasaki Prefecture}}, {{ill|Sasebo|en|Sasebo|qid=Q328000|lt=Sasebo City|1=Sasebo}}. Known locally as "Hachiman Shrine" or "Hachiman-sama," it is the largest shrine in the city.

== Overview ==
The shrine is located in the center of Sasebo City, northeast of the {{ill|Sasebo City Hall|ja|佐世保市役所|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasebo City Hall|1=Q11382539|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11382539}} and across from National Route 204. It is the only {{ill|Beppyo shrine|en|Beppyo shrine|qid=Q10898274|lt=Beppyo Shrine|1=Beppyo shrine}} in the city.

Within the grounds, there are a total of seven auxiliary shrines, including the Kameyama Inari Shrine.

== History ==
According to the shrine's tradition, it began in the 4th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|2=ja|3=天武天皇|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|2=ja|3=天武天皇|1=Emperor Tenmu|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q335181}} ({{ill|Hakuhō period|ja|白鳳|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakuhō period|1=Hakuhō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11580612}}) when a {{ill|Oracle|en|Oracle|qid=Q217123|lt=Oracle|1=Oracle}} led to the transfer of spirits from [[Usa Jingū]]

From the {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|qid=Q3125096|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era}} onwards, it became a guardian shrine for the naval personnel of the {{ill|Sasebo Naval District|ja|軍港佐世保|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasebo Naval District|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, but the shrine buildings were destroyed during the {{ill|Sasebo Air Raid|ja|佐世保空襲|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasebo Air Raid|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 佐世保大空襲|1=Bombing of Sasebo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11382525}} on June 29, 1945. The current buildings were rebuilt in 1964 using reinforced concrete.

Before World War II, it was finally Ranked as a {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|lt=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|lt=Prefectural shrine|ja|県社|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}}{{efn|Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural shrine|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q712534}}, and after the war, it became a Beppyo shrine of the {{ill|Association of Shinto Shrines|en|Association of Shinto Shrines|qid=Q908077|lt=Association of Shinto Shrines|1=Association of Shinto Shrines}}.

